;; macrophages are the first line of defence in the simulation
;; when a healthy cell gets eaten by bacteria, it releases a distress pheromone (p1)
;; macrophages detect that signal, move toward it, and eat the bacteria
;; after eating, macrophages leave their own pheromone (p2) used by the neutrophils

;; macrophage genome encoding:
;; A count --- sensitivity to p1 pheromone
;;             more A = lower detection threshold = reacts to fainter signals
;; G count --- max-eat: how many bacteria it can eat before dying of exhaustion
;; T and C are unused by macrophages (filled randomly)

;; immune recognition (self/non-self discrimination):
;; before eating, the macrophage compares the bacteria genome to the body-genome
;; using the genome-similarity score (0-1, based on Levenshtein distance)
;; if similarity >= lvenchisten-function/100 threshold: bacterium looks like healthy
;;   tissue — macrophage leaves it alone (bacterium gets times-fooled + 1)
;; if similarity <  lvenchisten-function/100 threshold: bacterium looks foreign —
;;   macrophage attacks and eats it

breed [macrophages macrophage]

;; p2 is the signal macrophages leave behind on grid patches after eating bacteria
;; neutrophils will follow this trail to find active infection sites
patches-own [
  macrophages-pheromone
]

macrophages-own [
  genome         ;; the 16-char dna string
  sensitivity    ;; how faint a p1 signal the macrophage can detect — from A count
  max-eat        ;; how many bacteria it can eat before dying of exhaustion — from G count
  eat-count      ;; how many bacteria this macrophage has eaten so far
  ticks-survived ;; how many ticks survived — used for fitness score in evolution
]

